        <mspace width="1em"/>
       </mtd>
       <mtd class="array" columnalign="left">
        <msubsup>
         <mrow>
          <mi>τ</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">I</mi>
          <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">P</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
         </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <mrow>
         <mo>(</mo>
         <mn>1</mn>
         <mo>−</mo>
         <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">f</mi>
         <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <msub>
         <mrow>
          <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">I</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">P</mi>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>−</mo>
        <msubsup>
         <mrow>
          <mi>τ</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">I</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mo>
          <mn>1</mn>
         </mrow>
        </msubsup>
        <msub>
         <mrow>
          <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">I</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">S</mi>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>≤</mo>
        <mn>0</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mspace width="0.16667em"/>
        <mspace width="0.16667em"/>
        <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">T</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
       </mtd>
      </mtr>
     </mtable>
    </mrow>
   </mfenced>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>The control is activated at 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e6998" display="inline" altimg="si86.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <mn>0</mn>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>; between 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7008" display="inline" altimg="si67.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">−</mo>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">o</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">f</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">f</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">s</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">e</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7035" display="inline" altimg="si86.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <mn>0</mn>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, the evolution of 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7045" display="inline" altimg="si172.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="normal">d</mi>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi>
    <mo>∕</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal">d</mi>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is given by Eq. 
 <xref rid="fd1j" ref-type="disp-formula">(1j)</xref> with 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7065" display="inline" altimg="si173.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">u</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <mn>0</mn>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. This particular optimal control problem can be put into the framework of Theorem 23.11 in Ref. 
 <xref rid="b22" ref-type="bibr">[22]</xref> – this framework provides the conditions such that, if there is at least one admissible process 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7079" display="inline" altimg="si174.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mo>(</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">u</mi>
    <mo>)</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> for which 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7094" display="inline" altimg="si247.svg">
   <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">J</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is finite, the optimal control problem admits a solution. The structure of the problem 
 <xref rid="fd15" ref-type="disp-formula">(15)</xref> is relatively simple, and to show that the conditions of Theorem 23.11 in Ref. 
 <xref rid="b22" ref-type="bibr">[22]</xref> apply here, it suffices to show that solutions 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7107" display="inline" altimg="si176.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> of the ordinary differential equation 
 <xref rid="fd1j" ref-type="disp-formula">(1j)</xref> remain in a bounded hypercube in 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7125" display="inline" altimg="si177.svg">
   <msup>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mn>6</mn>
    </mrow>
   </msup>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>; this is done in 
 <xref rid="appC" ref-type="sec">Appendix C</xref>. Furthermore, if the number of infectious individuals is sufficiently small at 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7139" display="inline" altimg="si86.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <mn>0</mn>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, then by making 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7150" display="inline" altimg="si179.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">u</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <mtext>Const.</mtext>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> sufficiently large, the solution 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7167" display="inline" altimg="si176.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mi>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> will follow a standard epidemic curve with 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e7180" display="inline" altimg="si253.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">k</mi>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">I</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">S</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">t</mi>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">≤</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-fraktur">B</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> – this gives the required admissible process.
</p>
